text.tspan: In most circumstances, multiple wires are needed to communicate between two devices, forming a bus.
In modern computers, "high" can be represented by anywhere from 1.8v to 12v and "low" can be represented by anything from -12v to 0v.
These wires are arranged in one of two manners, serial or parallel.
In digital systems, computers comunicate using a series of ones and zeroes, high and low voltages on a wire.
SPI is a clocked("synchronous") serial protocol, requiring four wires for two-way ("full duplex") communication.
